postcontent:
I'm selling a P250 Sub Compact chambered in 9mm, still "wearing" the SIG SAUER band, never been fired since factory. Selling because it was intentionally for my wife, but she prefers the clean break trigger of the M&P Shield over the double-action revolver style trigger of the P250.

The pistol comes New in box (only been dry-fired, never even gave it a new-gun bath in preparation to take to the range). It comes with two 12-round flush-fit magazines, gun lock, empty chamber indicator, hard case and sample gun oil. As an added bonus, I'll include one 50-round box of Freedom Munitions 9mm 115gr. REMAN ammunition for you to take it to the range without an extra stop at a store.

SIG SAUER has a long history of reliability and quality, and while I can't speak to its reliability, having never fired it, the gun feels good, and is very ergonomic. 

If you aren't familiar with the P250 line from SIG, it is a modular Polymer Pistol. The serialized component is the trigger mechanism, which can be taken out of the frame, and rather than purchase an entirely different firearm, you need only purchase the frame/barrel/slide assembly, and put the same trigger assembly in to have a completely new gun without the extra FFL paperwork. It's like having one lower assembly, and multiple upper assemblies for an AR.

title: For Sale:  Browning Maxus
postcontent:
Browning Maxus 3.5" in Mossy Oak's Duck Blind camo. 28" barrel, I'll include a Kick's High Flyer Full choke -- I won't need it without that Maxus. I also have the factory chokes.The Browning Maxus is a gas operated shotgun. According to the Browning website it's one that has one of the lowest perceived recoil of autoloading shotguns. The gas system is a newer system than the SX3, which shares the same system as the Browning Silver and has been around a while. The Maxus comes with shims to raise or drop the comb and add cast right or left. 

I've shot 1 ounce loads with no issues. I was actually very impressed as most 3.5" guns don't handle light loads as reliably as this did. I think my favorite part is how easy the handguard comes off. There is a lever up front that you pull on like you would on an over/under shotgun and the handguard just slides off. But when it's on, there's no wiggling. 

The Maxuses normally sell for around $1400-$1500 new depending on configuration. So if I were to sell mine I'd price it around $1300.

title: For Sale:  M1 Garand - 1943 Springfield **Price Reduced**
postcontent:
M1 Garand, which based upon serial number, (1.13m), was initially manufactured in February of 1943 .  SA 1/55 barrel, so it likely was last rebuilt by the military arsenal sometime in the spring of 1955.  The rifle was obtained from CMP (service grade) and has a new CMP walnut stock with very nice grain.  Barrel readings are outstanding - TE1+, ME 0+, well within specs of a brand new barrel.   This rifle exhibits the dark shading of the receiver heel due to the lead annealing.

I did apply 3 coats of BLO to the stock, as the wood was extremely dry, but otherwise the rifle is as received. I have not shot the rifle, but based upon the barrel readings and the extremely tight fit and lockup in the new stock, it should be an excellent shooting rifle.

Additional photos/information can be provided if desired.

Rifle includes CMP hard case; certificate; enbloc and armorer's hang tag.
Asking 980.00
